ovoked exclusionary measures against both groups. In addition, public health officials sought not only to restrict the entry of Mexicans (the majority of immigrants) during the 1920s but also to expel them during the 1930s. Abel’s revealing account provides a critical lens through which to view both the contemporary debate about immigration and the U.S. response to the emergent global tuberculosis epidemic.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aDiscrimination in medical carexHistoryx19th centuryxCaliforniaxLos Angeles. 0aDiscrimination in medical carexHistoryx20th centuryxCaliforniaxLos Angeles. 0aDiscrimination in medical carezCaliforniazLos AngelesxHistoryy19th century. 0aDiscrimination in medical carezCaliforniazLos AngelesxHistoryy20th century. 0aImmigrantsxDiseasesxHistoryx19th centuryxCaliforniaxLos Angeles. 0aImmigrantsxDiseasesxHistoryx20th centuryxCaliforniaxLos Angeles. 0aImmigrantsxDiseaseszCaliforniazLos AngelesxHistoryy19th century. 0aImmigrantsxDiseaseszCaliforniazLos AngelesxHistoryy20th century. 0aImmigrantsxMedical carexHistoryx19th centuryxCaliforniaxLos Angeles. 0aImmigrantsxMedical carexHistoryx20th centuryxCaliforniaxLos Angeles. 0aImmigrantsxMedical carezCaliforniazLos AngelesxHistoryy19th century. 0aImmigrantsxMedical carezCaliforniazLos AngelesxHistoryy20th century. 0aPublic healthxHistoryx19th centuryxCaliforniaxLos Angeles. 0aPublic healthxHistoryx20th centuryxCaliforniaxLos Angeles. 0aPublic healthzCaliforniazLos AngelesxHistoryy19th century. 0aPublic healthzCaliforniazLos AngelesxHistoryy20th century. 0aTuberculosisxHistoryx19th centuryxCaliforniaxLos Angeles. 0aTuberculosisxHistoryx20th centuryxCaliforniaxLos Angeles. 0aTuberculosiszCaliforniazLos AngelesxHistoryy19th century. 0